  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. These form a framework for countries to implement their own domestic laws and cooperate internationally to prevent and prosecute money laundering. Here are some of the most important:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988 Vienna Convention):** This convention was one of the first major international efforts to address money laundering, initially focusing on proceeds from drug trafficking. It requires signatory states to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from drug-related crimes and to cooperate in international investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000 Palermo Convention):** This convention expanded the scope of money laundering laws to cover proceeds from a wider range of serious crimes, including organized crime, corruption, and terrorism. It requires states to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from these crimes and to adopt measures for the confiscation of assets derived from illicit activities.\n\n*   **The International Convention for the Suppression of the Financing of Terrorism (1999):** This convention requires states to take measures to prevent and combat the financing of terrorism, including criminalizing the provision of funds for terrorist purposes and implementing measures to detect and freeze terrorist assets. While not solely focused on money laundering in",
